In this chapter, we discussed some critical issues regarding epidemics and their outbursts in static as well as dynamic network structures. We mainly focused on SIR and SIS models as well as identifying key strategies for identifying the damage caused in networks. We also discussed the various modeling techniques for studying cascading failures. Epidemics pass through populations and persists over long time periods. Thus, efficient modeling of the underlying network plays a crucial role in understanding the spread and prevention of an epidemic. Social, biological, and communication systems can be explained as complex networks with their degree distribution follows a power law, \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
